{"title_page": "Asepsis", "text_new": "{{About|the state of being free from pathogens|the process of achieving this state|Sterilization (microbiology)}}\n[[File:A day in the life of an OR technician 160920-F-AE629-070.jpg|thumb|Hand scrubbing procedure for surgery]]\n'''Asepsis''' is the state of being free from [[Pathogen|disease-causing micro-organisms]] (such as [[pathogenic bacteria]], [[virus|viruses]], [[pathogenic fungi]], and [[parasitism|parasites]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.registerednursing.org/nclex/standard-precautions-transmission-based-surgical-asepsis/|title=Standard Precautions, Transmission Based, Surgical Asepsis: NCLEX-RN {{!}}{{!}} RegisteredNursing.org|last=Burke|first=Alene|website=www.registerednursing.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> There are two categories of asepsis: medical and surgical.<ref name=\":0\" /> The modern day notion of asepsis is derived from the older [[antiseptic]] techniques, a shift initiated by different individuals in the 19th century who introduced practices such as the sterilizing of surgical tools and the wearing of surgical gloves during operations.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Markel|first=Howard|title=An Anatomy of Addiction|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> The goal of asepsis is to eliminate infection, not to achieve sterility.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ideally, a surgical field is [[Sterilization (microbiology)|sterile]], meaning it is free of all biological contaminants (e.g. fungi, bacteria, viruses), not just those that can cause disease, [[putrefaction]], or [[fermentation]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Even in an aseptic state, a condition of sterile inflammation may develop.The term often refers to those practices used to promote or induce asepsis in an operative field of [[surgery]] or [[medicine]] to prevent [[infection]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Grace Y.|last2=Nu\u00f1ez|first2=Gabriel|date=19 November 2010|title=Sterile inflammation: sensing and reacting to damage|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3114424/|journal=Nature reviews. Immunology|volume=10|issue=12|pages=826\u2013837|doi=10.1038/nri2873|issn=1474-1733|pmc=3114424|pmid=21088683|via=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe modern concept of asepsis evolved in the 19th century through multiple individuals. [[Ignaz Semmelweis]] showed that [[hand washing]] prior to delivery reduced [[puerperal fever]]. Despite this, many hospitals continued to practice surgery in unsanitary conditions, with some surgeons taking pride in their bloodstained operating gowns.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Millard|first=Candice|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/destiny-of-the-republic-a-tale-of-madness-medicine-and-the-murder-of-a-president/oclc/700205578|title=Destiny of the republic: a tale of madness, medicine and the murder of a president|date=2011|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=978-0-385-52626-5|location=New York|language=English|oclc=700205578}}</ref> It was not until after reading of the findings by [[Louis Pasteur]] that [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]] introduced the use of [[carbolic acid]] as an antiseptic, and in doing so, reduced surgical infection rates.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Schlich|first=Thomas|date=July 2012|title=Asepsis and Bacteriology: A Realignment of Surgery and Laboratory Science1|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3426977/|journal=Medical History|volume=56|issue=3|pages=308\u2013334|doi=10.1017/mdh.2012.22|issn=0025-7273|pmc=3426977|pmid=23002302|via=}}</ref> [[Lawson Tait]] shifted the movement then from antisepsis to asepsis, instilling practices such as a strict no-talking policy within his operating room and drastically limiting the number of people to come in contact with a patient's wound.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flack|first=Harvey|url=http://europepmc.org/backend/ptpmcrender.fcgi?accid=PMC1940203&blobtype=pdf|title=Lawson Tait|publisher=Thomas Vicary Lecture|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> [[Ernst von Bergmann]] also introduced the [[autoclave]], a device used for the practice of the sterilization of surgical instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/503947|title=History of Infection Control and its Contributions to the|website=Medscape|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n[[File:William Stewart Halsted.jpg|thumb|Image of William Stewart Halsted]]\nBut, everything from operating room uniforms to gloves was pioneered by [[William Stewart Halsted|William Halsted]]. Preceding modern-day scrubs attire, Halsted implemented a no street clothes policy in his operating room, opting to wear a completely white, sterile uniform consisting of a duck suit, tennis shoes, and skullcap.<ref name=\":1\" /> This helped to prevent the introduction of infections into open wounds.<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, Halsted would sterilize the operation site with alcohol, iodine and other disinfectants and use drapes to cover all areas except for the site.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his department at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]], he enforced an extreme hand washing ritual consisting of soaking in harmfully strong chemicals like permanganate and mercury bichloride solution as well as scrubbing with stiff brushes.<ref name=\":1\" /> The damage to a surgical nurse's hands compelled him to create the earliest form of the [[Medical glove|surgical gloves]] with the [[Goodyear Rubber Company]].<ref name=\":1\" /> These gloves became a part of the aseptic surgery standard when Dr. [[Joseph Colt Bloodgood]] and several others began wearing them for that particular purpose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://portraitcollection.jhmi.edu/portraits/halsted-william-3|title=William Stewart Halsted|website=portraitcollection.jhmi.edu|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Antisepsis vs. Asepsis ===\nThe line between antisepsis and asepsis is interpreted differently, depending on context and time.<ref name=\":3\" /> In the past, antiseptic operations occurred in people's homes or in operating theaters before a large crowd.<ref name=\":3\" /> Procedures for implementing antisepsis varied among physicians and experienced constant changes.<ref name=\":3\" /> Until the late 19th century, physicians rejected the connection between Louis Pasteur's [[Germ theory of disease|germ theory]] that bacteria caused diseases and antiseptic techniques.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/guides/zq8xk2p/revision/5|title=Developments in bacteriology - Attempts to prevent illness and disease \u2013 WJEC - GCSE History Revision - WJEC|website=BBC Bitesize|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> At the end of the 19th century, Joseph Lister and his followers expanded the term \"antisepsis\" and coined \"asepsis,\" with the justification that Lister had initially \"suggested excluding septic agents from the wound from the start.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> Generally, however, asepsis is seen as a continuation of antisepsis since many of the values are the same, such as a \"germ-free environment around the wound or patient,\" and techniques pioneered under both names are used in conjunction today.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n==Method==\nAsepsis refers to any procedure that is performed under sterile conditions. This includes medical and laboratory techniques (such as with [[Microbiological culture|bacterial cultures]]). There are two types of asepsis &ndash; medical and surgical.<ref name=\":0\" /> Medical or clean asepsis reduces the number of organisms and prevents their spread; surgical or sterile asepsis includes procedures to eliminate [[micro-organism]]s from an area and is practiced by [[surgical technologist]]s and nurses.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ultimately, though, successful usage of aseptic operations depends on a combination of preparatory actions.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.uci.edu/compliance/animalcare-use/research-policies-and-guidance/surgery-asepsis.html|title=Aseptic Surgery|website=research.uci.edu|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> For example, sterile equipment and fluids are used during invasive medical and nursing procedures.<ref name=\":4\" /> The largest manifestation of such aseptic techniques is in hospital [[Operating theatre|operating theaters]], where the aim is to keep patients free from [[Nosocomial infection|hospital micro-organisms]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.in.gov/isdh/files/l51.pdf|title=Medical Asepsis (Clean Technique)|last=|first=|date=|website=Indiana Department of Health|format=PDF|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n[[File:Scalpel blade 01.JPG|thumb|Packaged, sterilized surgical instruments]]\nWhile all members of the surgical team should demonstrate good aseptic technique, it is the role of the [[Perioperative Nursing#Scrub Nurse|scrub nurse]] or surgical technologist to set up and maintain the sterile field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencebuddies.org/mentoring/project_ideas/MicroBio_Techniques.shtml|title=Microbiology Techniques & Troubleshooting|website=Science Buddies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ruf.rice.edu/~bioslabs/bios318/318manual.htm#aseptic|title=Bios 318 Microbiology methods manual|website=www.ruf.rice.edu}}</ref> To prevent cross-contamination of patients, instruments are sterilized through [[autoclaving]] or by using disposable equipment; [[Surgical suture|suture]] material or [[Xenograft|xenografts]] also need to be sterilized beforehand.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Yool|first=Donald A.|title=Small Animal Soft Tissue Surgery|publisher=CABI|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Basic aseptic procedures includes hand washing, donning protective gloves, masks and gowns, and sterilizing equipment and linens.<ref name=\":5\" /> Medical aseptic techniques also includes curbing the spread of [[Infection|infectious diseases]] through quarantine, specifically isolation procedures based on the mode of disease transmission.<ref name=\":5\" /> Within contact, droplet and airborne isolation methods, two different procedures emerge: strict isolation vs. reverse isolation.<ref name=\":5\" /> Strict isolation quarantines patients to prevent them from infecting others, while reverse isolation prevents vulnerable patients from becoming infected.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Related Infections ==\nIn aseptic conditions, a \"chronic low-level inflammation\" known as sterile inflammation may develop as a result of trauma, stress, or environmental factors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Feldman|first=Noa|last2=Rotter-Maskowitz|first2=Aviva|last3=Okun|first3=Eitan|date=2015-11-01|title=DAMPs as mediators of sterile inflammation in aging-related pathologies|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1568163715000057|journal=Ageing Research Reviews|series=Damage-associated molecular patterns and their pathological relevance in ageing|language=en|volume=24|pages=29\u201339|doi=10.1016/j.arr.2015.01.003|issn=1568-1637}}</ref> As in infections caused by pathogens or microbes, the immune response is regulated by host receptors.<ref name=\":2\" /> Tissue damage resulting from non-infectious means are caused by [[DAMPs]] molecules released after injury or cell death has occurred, which are able to stimulate inflammation response.<ref name=\":2\" /> Diseases associated with sterile inflammation include [[Alzheimer's disease]], [[atherosclerosis]], as well as cancer [[Neoplasm|tumor]] growth due to \"immune cell infiltration.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, aseptic tissue damage may arise from corticosteroid injections, which are drugs used to treat musculoskeletal conditions such as [[Carpal tunnel syndrome|carpal tunnel]] and [[osteoarthritis]], though this tends to result from improper aseptic technique.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/treatment-tests-and-therapies/injectable-corticosteroids|title=Injectable Corticosteroids|website=www.hopkinsmedicine.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Holland|first=Christian|last2=Jaeger|first2=Lothar|last3=Smentkowski|first3=Ulrich|last4=Weber|first4=Beate|last5=Otto|first5=Christina|date=15 June 2012|title=Septic and Aseptic Complications of Corticosteroid Injections|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3394381/|journal=Deutsches \u00c4rzteblatt International|volume=109|issue=24|pages=425\u2013430|doi=10.3238/arztebl.2012.0425|issn=1866-0452|pmc=3394381|pmid=22787504|via=}}</ref>\n[[File:Staphylococcus Bacteria.jpg|thumb|Medical illustration of Staphylococcus]]\nDespite efforts to preserve asepsis during surgery, there still persists a 1-3% chance of a [[surgical site infection]] (SSI).<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/health/conditions-and-diseases/surgical-site-infections|title=Surgical Site Infections|website=www.hopkinsmedicine.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> Infections are categorized as superficial incisional, deep incisional, or organ; the first type are confined to the skin, the second to muscles and nearby tissues, and the third to organs not anatomically close to the operation site.<ref name=\":6\" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.urmc.rochester.edu/encyclopedia/content.aspx?contenttypeid=134&contentid=144|title=Surgical Site Infections - Health Encyclopedia - University of Rochester Medical Center|website=www.urmc.rochester.edu|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>The exact modes of infection depend on the types of surgery, but the most common bacteria that are responsible for SSIs are Staphylococcus aureus, coagulase-negative staphylococci, Escherichia coli, and Enterococcus spp.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Owens|first=C. D.|last2=Stoessel|first2=K.|date=November 2008|title=Surgical site infections: epidemiology, microbiology and prevention|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19022115|journal=The Journal of Hospital Infection|volume=70 Suppl 2|pages=3\u201310|doi=10.1016/S0195-6701(08)60017-1|issn=0195-6701|pmid=19022115|via=}}</ref> The [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] emphasizes the importance of both antiseptic and aseptic approaches in avoiding SSIs, especially since Staphylococcus aureus, among other bacteria, are able to evolve drug-resistant strains that can be difficult to treat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/news/080401_mrsa|title=Superbug, super-fast evolution|website=evolution.berkeley.edu|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> In 2017, nearly 20,000 patients in the United States died from Staphylococcus aureus in comparison to the 16,350 from diagnosed HIV.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kourtis|first=Athena P.|date=2019|title=Vital Signs: Epidemiology and Recent Trends in Methicillin-Resistant and in Methicillin-Susceptible Staphylococcus aureus Bloodstream Infections \u2014 United States|url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/68/wr/mm6809e1.htm|journal=MMWR. Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report|language=en-us|volume=68|doi=10.15585/mmwr.mm6809e1|issn=0149-2195}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/hiv/basics/statistics.html|title=Basic Statistics {{!}} HIV Basics {{!}} HIV/AIDS {{!}} CDC|date=2020-03-20|website=www.cdc.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Antiseptic]]\n*[[Barrier nursing]]\n*[[Body substance isolation]]\n*[[Cleanliness]]\n*[[Contamination control]]\n*[[Disinfectant]] (measurements of effectiveness)\n*[[Ignaz Semmelweis]]\n*[[Sterilization (microbiology)]]\n*[[Transmission-based precautions]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Surgery]]\n[[Category:Antiseptics]]\n[[Category:Medical hygiene]]\n[[Category:Microbiology techniques]]\n[[Category:Sterilization (microbiology)]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the state of being free from pathogens|the process of achieving this state|Sterilization (microbiology)}}\n[[File:A day in the life of an OR technician 160920-F-AE629-070.jpg|thumb|Hand scrubbing procedure for surgery]]\n'''Asepsis''' is the state of being free from [[Pathogen|disease-causing micro-organisms]] (such as [[pathogenic bacteria]], [[virus|viruses]], [[pathogenic fungi]], and [[parasitism|parasites]]).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.registerednursing.org/nclex/standard-precautions-transmission-based-surgical-asepsis/|title=Standard Precautions, Transmission Based, Surgical Asepsis: NCLEX-RN {{!}}{{!}} RegisteredNursing.org|last=RN|first=Alene BurkeAlene Burke|last2=City|first2=MSN is a nationally recognized nursing educator She began her work career as an elementary school teacher in New York|website=www.registerednursing.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-21|last3=hospital|first3=later attended Queensborough Community College for her associate degree in nursing She worked as a registered nurse in the critical care area of a local community|last4=Time|first4=At This|last5=College|first5=she was committed to become a nursing educator She got her bachelor\u2019s of science in nursing with Excelsior|last6=University|first6=a part of the New York State|last7=Isl|first7=immediately upon graduation she began graduate school at Adelphi University on Long|last8=Education|first8=New York She graduated Summa Cum Laude from Adelphi with a double masters degree in both Nursing|last9=Administration|first9=Nursing}}</ref> There are two categories of asepsis: medical and surgical.<ref name=\":0\" /> The modern day notion of asepsis is derived from the older [[antiseptic]] techniques, a shift initiated by different individuals in the 19th century who introduced practices such as the sterilizing of surgical tools and the wearing of surgical gloves during operations.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Markel|first=Howard|title=An Anatomy of Addiction|publisher=Pantheon Books|year=|isbn=|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> The goal of asepsis is to eliminate infection, not to achieve sterility.<ref name=\":0\" /> Ideally, a surgical field is [[Sterilization (microbiology)|sterile]], meaning it is free of all biological contaminants (e.g. fungi, bacteria, viruses), not just those that can cause disease, [[putrefaction]], or [[fermentation]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Even in an aseptic state, a condition of sterile inflammation may develop.The term often refers to those practices used to promote or induce asepsis in an operative field of [[surgery]] or [[medicine]] to prevent [[infection]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Chen|first=Grace Y.|last2=Nu\u00f1ez|first2=Gabriel|date=19 November 2010|title=Sterile inflammation: sensing and reacting to damage|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3114424/|journal=Nature reviews. Immunology|volume=10|issue=12|pages=826\u2013837|doi=10.1038/nri2873|issn=1474-1733|pmc=3114424|pmid=21088683|via=}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe modern concept of asepsis evolved in the 19th century through multiple individuals. [[Ignaz Semmelweis]] showed that [[hand washing]] prior to delivery reduced [[puerperal fever]]. Despite this, many hospitals continued to practice surgery in unsanitary conditions, with some surgeons taking pride in their bloodstained operating gowns.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Millard|first=Candice|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/destiny-of-the-republic-a-tale-of-madness-medicine-and-the-murder-of-a-president/oclc/700205578|title=Destiny of the republic: a tale of madness, medicine and the murder of a president|date=2011|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=978-0-385-52626-5|location=New York|language=English|oclc=700205578}}</ref> It was not until after reading of the findings by [[Louis Pasteur]] that [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]] introduced the use of [[carbolic acid]] as an antiseptic, and in doing so, reduced surgical infection rates.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Schlich|first=Thomas|date=July 2012|title=Asepsis and Bacteriology: A Realignment of Surgery and Laboratory Science1|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3426977/|journal=Medical History|volume=56|issue=3|pages=308\u2013334|doi=10.1017/mdh.2012.22|issn=0025-7273|pmc=3426977|pmid=23002302|via=}}</ref> [[Lawson Tait]] shifted the movement then from antisepsis to asepsis, instilling practices such as a strict no-talking policy within his operating room and drastically limiting the number of people to come in contact with a patient's wound.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Flack|first=Harvey|url=http://europepmc.org/backend/ptpmcrender.fcgi?accid=PMC1940203&blobtype=pdf|title=Lawson Tait|publisher=Thomas Vicary Lecture|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> [[Ernst von Bergmann]] also introduced the [[autoclave]], a device used for the practice of the sterilization of surgical instruments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/503947|title=History of Infection Control and its Contributions to the|website=Medscape|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n[[File:William Stewart Halsted.jpg|thumb|Image of William Stewart Halsted]]\nBut, everything from operating room uniforms to gloves was pioneered by [[William Stewart Halsted|William Halsted]]. Preceding modern-day scrubs attire, Halsted implemented a no street clothes policy in his operating room, opting to wear a completely white, sterile uniform consisting of a duck suit, tennis shoes, and skullcap.<ref name=\":1\" /> This helped to prevent the introduction of infections into open wounds.<ref name=\":1\" /> Additionally, Halsted would sterilize the operation site with alcohol, iodine and other disinfectants and use drapes to cover all areas except for the site.<ref name=\":1\" /> In his department at [[Johns Hopkins Hospital]], he enforced an extreme hand washing ritual consisting of soaking in harmfully strong chemicals like permanganate and mercury bichloride solution as well as scrubbing with stiff brushes.<ref name=\":1\" /> The damage to a surgical nurse's hands compelled him to create the earliest form of the [[Medical glove|surgical gloves]] with the [[Goodyear Rubber Company]].<ref name=\":1\" /> These gloves became a part of the aseptic surgery standard when Dr. [[Joseph Colt Bloodgood]] and